ce:section.ce:para:
It was reported by our group that CDs containing dodecyl benzenesulfonate (DBS) layered double hydroxides (LDHs) nanocatalyst behaved as an operative heterogeneous Fenton resembling catalyst for decomposition of acidified H2O2 to generate abundant •OH [13]. The mechanism of reaction was illustrated as, first, CDs assembled on the outward of DBS-LDHs, donate an electron to H2O2 to produce •OH radicals. Being an effective oxidant •OH radicals smoothly attacks DBS molecules at the surface of LDHs to produce SO4
                        2− ions and excited SO2*. Meanwhile, excited SO2* might transfer its energy to neighboring CDs to produce excited CDs*. Lastly, excited CDs reverted to ground states with strong CL emission (Fig. 8
                        ). Two peaks were detected in this CL system. The peak at 430nm was attributed to emission of excited SO2* while peak at 490nm was accredited to emission from CDs*, formed by CRET from SO2*. The mechanism of the system was well elaborated but the analytical utility of the system has not checked.

The application of CDs to acidic oxidants (Ce(IV) and KMnO4) caused CL emission [12]. In CDs–Ce(IV) system, Ce(IV) transformed to Ce(III) and an electron transfer from CDs to Ce(IV) was advocated. In addition, it was indicated that KMnO4 could inject holes into CDs and was reduced to Mn2+*. Whereas, excited Mn2+* could account partly for CL emission. As a whole two emission bands were detected in KMnO4
                        CDs system. The first one locating around 500nm was reasonably ascribed to radiative recombination of oxidant-injected holes and electrons in CDs. In fact, electrons in excited state annihilate with holes to produce CL. The second one located at 650nm, matched with the phosphorescence of Mn2+ (4T1 to 6A1 transition) (Fig. 10
                        ). The mechanism of the CL system was elaborated in detail but they have not checked any analytical application of the enhanced system.
